                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d783">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/4134</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SAG1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schmedeman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Christiania</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-28T15:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 28, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 4.20 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>166. Department’s circular of March 16, 2 p.m. I have received from the Minister
                    for Foreign Affairs a note dated April 26 in which he states that “the Norwegian
                    Government is obliged to reserve to itself the right to make a decision in each
                    separate case where a merchant vessel belonging to a belligerent power and with
                    such an armed guard on board might enter a Norwegian port.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SAG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Schmedeman</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
